<font color="#FF0000">COMING OUT OF THE RICE PADDIES</font><br>
<tt>Sat Nov  8 23:57:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Michael;<br>
Prayer has always been a means for deep intercession, a source for filling in that need that can only be satisfied by his presence. It was all right for the Jew to cry out loud to his God, and it is still all right to do so today. Many a night I have spent in the wilderness, speaking out loud to the God of Abraham, Isaac and Israel. There is nothing like standing in the presence of He that brought us through so much. To Praise and thank Him for what I do have and not for what I don’t possess. <br><br>
Last year I began to search for those I had shared so many hard, good and precious times together in Vietnam. It took some time but it was all well worth it. There is nothing like finding a lost buddy, to recall those times together. After months of searching I had found 29 Marines from my platoon. 12 of us got together in February and then another 9 joined 3 of us that were able to get together with 20 other Marines from our company. For the most part none of us had seen, or had spoken to another Marinefrom our company in over 30 years. <br><br>
That reunion brought a lot of closure that I was not aware I needed. It also opened new channels of trust, understanding and unity like that we had once shared in Nam. There is nothing like it.<br>
The Internet helped me find a lot of them, but it wasn’t easy especially when I could only remember the nicknames we had for each other. But, finding one Marine led to the name of another and  so forth. <br><br>
Before last year I hadn’t given it much though other then to just remember faint faces, now I am so glad that I took that step in reaching out. It answered a lot and fill in that void. What was surprising was how each one of us had in his own way realized how much we all meant to each other and how God had protected us all under some very dangerous and uncommon enemy encounters. <br><br>
I don't know if its a new coming of age for us or perhaps we are experiencing a new awareness of what we accomplished together. There is nothing like sitting around and recalling those memories with those we shared so much. What was surprising was how we all recalled so much, remembered the good, the bad and the ugly but it did bring in a new comfort, a comfort similar to what I had only experienced in prayer and alone with God. Perhaps somehow it is all spiritually united. Something about warriors and trust in God.<br><br>
Perhaps it was also because of the honor I felt to be among so many good men, individuals that love their country, believed in what we did and who supported what I did and appreciated that I was there as much as I supported and appreciated that they were there. <br>
Welcome home, Michael from those of us that have also found ourselves pinned down in the very deep rice paddies of life. <br><br>

